<HEADLINE>
<P>
FISH REPORT: BASS, TROUT ARE ACTIVE AT PYRAMID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Striped bass fishing at Pyramid Lake has been picking up in recent weeks and 
fishermen lucky enough to be at that northern Los Angeles County reservoir when 
trout are being stocked are hitting the jackpot. 
</P>
<P>
Lester Carpenter of Lebec caught and released seven stripers weighing 46 1/2 
pounds; Paul Selkirk of Simi Valley caught and released nine totaling 68 
pounds, the largest an 18-pounder, and Ron Morgan of Granada Hills caught four 
stripers, including a 23-pounder. 
</P>
<P>
All were fishing while the Department of Fish and Game was dumping its 
bi-weekly allotment of trout -- a favorite food of the striped bass -- into the 
marina. 
</P>
<P>
WILLOW BEACH -- Striped bass biting best downriver in deep water. Robert 
Pingel, Utah, 17-4 striper, caught between Mile Markers 35-36. Pan-sized trout 
biting downriver at Mile Marker 41, with corn and cheese working best. Some 
bigger fish being caught upriver. One weighed in at 4-2. Nightcrawlers best 
bet. 
</P>
<P>
LAKE MEAD -- Striped bass biting throughout Overton Arm. Some action at Vegas 
Wash and dam, but fish are smaller. Anchovies best bet. Largemouth bass picking 
up, biting best in Overton Arm. Coves producing best elsewhere. Live bait 
working best. Catfish just beginning to bite. 
</P>
<P>
BULLHEAD CITY -- Striped bass averaging two to four pounds, with an occasional 
big fish. Bob Davis, Bullhead City, 25-0 striper, largest this year, caught 
drifting anchovies on river. Trout biting best in river, with Berkley Power 
Bait working best. Lake: Trollers using needlefish lures at 50-60 feet doing 
best for trout. Largemouth bass biting off points at about 20 feet. 
</P>
<P>
SALTON SEA -- Orangemouth corvina biting, mainly at Red Hill, with fish 
averaging 12-15 pounds. Live bait and artificials working. Croaker biting at 
Bombay Beach. Sargo scattered. 
</P>
<P>
LAKE CACHUMA -- Largemouth bass and catfish biting in shallow water. Ray 
DeVreugh, Gilroy, 5 1/2- and four pound bass. Ron Pruden, Orange, four catfish, 
40 pounds, largest 20 pounds. Redear perch biting at 20 feet along shoreline, 
one weighed in at 2 1/2 pounds. Trout biting on most baits. 
</P>
<P>
LAKE CASITAS -- Catfish bite excellent, best at dam or Sunken Island at 35 
feet. John Higuera, Santa Barbara, 19-pound catfish. Largemouth bass biting at 
8-10 feet, with bigger fish taking crawfish and nightcrawlers. Plastic worms 
working best for smaller fish. Several limits of trout, most coming from 
Wadleigh and Santa Ana arms. Redear perch biting near dock at Wadleigh Arm. Red 
worms best bet. Lake's new hours are from 6 a.m. to 7:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
PYRAMID LAKE -- Striped bass biting between channel and marina. Scott Mueller, 
Northridge, four stripers, largest eight pounds, released. Largemouth bass bite 
scattered. Greg Peterson, Pasadena, five largemouths averaging three pounds. 
Brian Goldsmith, Pasadena, five smallmouths, largest 3 1/2-pounds. 
</P>
<P>
IRVINE LAKE -- Trout in the 10-pound class still active, but other species 
picking up. Largemouth bass and crappie biting in shallow water. Jim Shaffer, 
Garden Grove, 7 1/2-pound bass. Bob Pitman, Hacienda Heights, two-pound 
crappie. 
</P>
<P>
LAKE SKINNER -- Trout biting at dam. Jerry Boison, Anaheim, 3 1/2-pound trout. 
Catfish and largemouth bass biting throughout lake in shallows. Tom Kente, 
Whittier, five-pound bass. Robert Luna, Colton, 5 3/4-pound bass. Gary Venuer, 
7 1/4-pound catfish. Roy Sena, Anaheim, 5 1/2-pound catfish. 
</P>
<P>
BIG BEAR -- Fishing good for trout. Shore fishermen using standard baits and 
trollers using nightcrawlers behind flashers catching trout to 2 1/2-pounds. 
Largemouth bass moving into shallow water, but few caught. 
</P>
<P>
SILVERWOOD LAKE -- Largemouth and striped bass biting primarily in channel. Joe 
Duyton, Riverside, 10 1/4-pound largemouth. Greg Silks, Alta Loma, 18-pound 
striper, caught at 30 feet. 
</P>
<P>
Saltwater 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Trout Plants 
</P>
<P>
A list of waters scheduled to be planted by the Department of Fish and Game, 
weather and road conditions permitting, by counties: 
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Arroyo Seco Creek, Upper and Lower Big Tujunga Creek, El Dordao 
Park Lake, Jackson Lake, Little Rock Creek, Little Rock Reservoir, Malibu 
Creek, Peck Road Park Lake, Piru Creek (Frenchman's Flat), Puddingstone Lake, 
San Dimas Reservoir. 
</P>
<P>
SAN BERNARDINO -- Big Bear Lake, Prado Park Lake, Silverwood Lake. 
</P>
<P>
