<P>
Imprisoned members of West Germany's extremist Red Army Faction rejected an 
offer of mediation by parliamentary leader Rita Suessmuth and will continue a 
63-day-old hunger strike "even if it means they starve to death," their 
attorneys said in Bonn. The lawyers said the Red Army members will stop their 
fast only if authorities meet their demand to be moved from separate cells 
among those of other inmates to common holding areas where they can be 
together. Thirty-eight Red Army activists and sympathizers imprisoned at 
various sites around West Germany have taken part in the hunger strike. 
