<P>
POLAND'S REFORMS IN PERIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Demands for more concessions from the Polish government threatened to unravel a 
sweeping reform package agreed to in marathon talks among official 
representatives and leaders of key Polish opposition, business and church 
groups. Shipyard workers and farmers joined official Communist trade unions in 
opposing the complex agreement, but Solidarity union founder Lech Walesa said 
he remains confident that opposition leaders will sign a pact with the 
government. The signing ceremony has been scheduled for today. The agreement 
calls for re-legalization of the outlawed Solidarity union, partially free 
elections to Poland's nominal Parliament and other political reforms. 
</P>
