<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
BAN ON IMPORTING SEMIAUTOMATIC GUNS EXPANDING, WHITE HOUSE SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bush Administration said today that it is expanding a recently imposed ban 
on the importation of semiautomatic assault weapons. 
</P>
<P>
White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said President Bush accepted a 
Treasury Department recommendation that the ban be widened, effective 
immediately. 
</P>
<P>
The action expands the ban to cover all imports of the high-powered, rapid-fire 
weapons, Fitzwater said. The previous ban, announced in early March, covered 
only about 80% of imports, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Fitzwater said the initial ban on such weapons, including the AK-47 assault 
rifle, was aimed at fostering "a climate in which reasonable and well-intended 
people . . . could work out a thoughtful solution" to the proliferation of such 
weapons. He said the department is imposing a ban on an additional 24 types of 
guns "to review their suitability for sporting purposes." 
</P>
</TEXT>
